Loading required packages

First, the required packages have to be loaded. You can access to the overview of the packages on Github. The simulation data will be generated by using the package sna. Then, by using these generated data, NAM will be fitted by using the function lnam.

library(sna)


The Simulation Study

We performed a two-stage simulation study to examine the performance of Bayes factor for testing \(\beta\) coefficients. First, we conducted a two-sided test for \(\beta\). Specifically, we tested the following hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) and \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\). In order to do that we have applied two different methodology for calculating the Bayes factor; Savage-dickey density ratio and Bayesian Information Criteria (BIC). In particular, we explored which Bayes factor converges fastest to the true hypothesis and assesed the sensitivity of Bayes factors calculated with two different approach. Second, we conducted a multiple hypothesis for \(\beta\) coefficients with a precise hypothesis and two interval hypothesis: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) versus \(H_{1}: \beta > 0\) versus \(H_{2}: \beta < 0\). For the two-sided hypothesis testing, we only used Savage-dickey Bayes factor approach. We particularly considered the following network autocorrelation model with one-covariate and an intercept value;

\[ \begin{align*} y = \beta_{0} + X\beta_1 + \rho Wy + \epsilon, \qquad \epsilon &\sim {\sf Norm}(0, \sigma^2I_g) \end{align*} \]


Two-Sided Hypothesis Testing: Savage Dickey Ratio Approach

The Following Function bf_averages generates network autocorrelation model data using the specified parameters as input variables. Then it tests hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) and \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\) for the simulated data and calculates the \(B_{01}\) using the Savage-Dickey ratio method with unit information prior.

It returns 20X4 matrix:

  • In the columns: Average Bayes Factor (\(B_{01}\)) and average of \(log(B_{01})\) for the \(\beta_{1}\).
  • In the rows: Beta sequence of 20 between -2 and 2.


Input variables:

  • sigma2 : \(\sigma^{2}\)
  • n : \(g\), network size
  • rho : \(\rho\), network effect
  • d : \(d\), network density
bf_averages <- function(sigma2 = 1, n = 50, rho = 0.2, d = 0.2){
  
  beta_seq <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = 20) #Beta Sequence 
  BF_averages_1 <- c() #for the average of 1000 B01
  BF_log_averages_1 <- c()  #for the average of 1000 log(B01)
  
  for (i in 1: 20){
   
    beta <- cbind(rep(1, 1000),rep(beta_seq[i], 1000)) #Covariate Matrix
    BayesFactor_B1 <- c() #B01 Arrays for for Beta1 estimates
    
    #Network Autocorrelation Data Generation 
    
    for (j in 1:1000){
      set.seed(123)
      Wadj <- sna::rgraph(n, tprob = d, mode = "graph")
      W <- sna::make.stochastic(Wadj, mode = "row") 
      X <- matrix(c(rep(1, n), rnorm(n*1)), nrow=n, ncol=2)
      
      y <- c((solve(diag(n) - rho*W))%*%(X%*%beta[j,] + rnorm(n, sd = sqrt(sigma2))))
      y <- y - mean(y)
      
      model1 <- sna::lnam(y, X, W)#network autocorrelation model fit
    
      #Bayes Factor Calculation for Beta1 
      post1 <- dnorm(0, mean = model1$beta[2,1], model1$beta.se[2]) #posterior distribution
      prior1 <- dnorm(0, mean = model1$beta[2,1], model1$beta.se[2]*sqrt(n)) #unit information prior distribution
      fact1 <- post1/prior1
      BayesFactor_B1 <- c(BayesFactor_B1, fact1)
    }
    BF_averages_1 <- c(BF_averages_1, mean(BayesFactor_B1))
    BF_log_averages_1 <- c(BF_log_averages_1, mean(log(BayesFactor_B1)))
  }
  results <- cbind(BF_averages_1, BF_log_averages_1)
  return(results)
}

Two-Sided Hypothesis Testing: BIC Approximation

The Following Function bic_averages generates network autocorrelation model data using the specified parameters as input variables. Then it tests hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) and \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\) for the simulated data and calculates the \(B_{01}\) using the BIC approximation.

It returns 20X5 matrix:

  • In the columns: BIC scores for the models where beta is excluded (\(H_{0}\)) and included (\(H_{1}\)) respectively. Bayes Factor (\(B_{01}\)) calculated based on the BIC approximation, posterior probabilities and average of \(log(B_{01})\).
  • In the rows: Beta sequence of 20 between -2 and 2.


Input variables:

  • sigma2 : \(\sigma^{2}\)
  • n : \(g\), network size
  • rho : \(\rho\), network effect
  • d : \(d\), network density


bic_averages <- function(sigma2 = 1, n = 50, rho = 0.2, d = 0.2){
  
  beta_seq <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = 20) #Beta Sequence 
  BIC_averages0 <- c() #the averages of 1000 BIC scores of model H0 for each beta
  BIC_averages1 <- c() # the averages of 1000 BIC scores of model H1 for each beta
  BF_01_averages <- c() # the averages of 1000 B01 for each beta
  BF_post_averages <- c() # the averages of 1000 posterior probability of B01 for each beta
  log_averages <- c() #the averages of 1000 log(B01) for each beta
  
  for (i in 1: 20){ #for each beta value

    beta <- cbind(rep(1, 1000),rep(beta_seq[i], 1000)) #Covariate Matrix
    BIC_H0 <- c() #BIC scores of model H0 for the specified beta1
    BIC_H1 <- c() #BIC scores of model H0 for the specified beta1
    BF_01 <- c()  #B01 
    BF_post <- c() #posterior probabilities
    
    for (j in 1:1000){ 
      
      #Network Autocorrelation Data Generation
      set.seed(123)
      Wadj <- sna::rgraph(n, tprob = d, mode = "graph")
      W <- sna::make.stochastic(Wadj, mode = "row") 
      X <- matrix(c(rep(1, n), rnorm(n*1)), nrow=n, ncol=2)
      y <- c((solve(diag(n) - rho*W))%*%(X%*%beta[j,] + rnorm(n, sd = sqrt(sigma2))))
      y <- y - mean(y)
      
      model_H1 <- sna::lnam(y, X, W) #network autocorrelation model fit (beta 1 included)
      
      #BIC Calculation
      res1 <- model_H1$residuals
      w <- rep(1, n)
      ll1<- model_H1$lnlik.model
      bic1 <- -2 * ll1  + 4*log(n)
      BIC_H1 <- c(BIC_H1, bic1)
      
      
      model_H0 <- sna::lnam(y, X[,1], W) #network autocorrelation model fit (beta 1 IS NOT included)
      
      
      #BIC Calculation
      res0 <- model_H0$residuals
      w <- rep(1, n)
      ll0<- model_H0$lnlik.model
      bic0 <- -2 * ll0  + 3*log(n)
      BIC_H0 <- c(BIC_H0, bic0)
      
      #Bayes Factor Calculation from BIC 
      bf <- exp(-(bic0 - bic1)/2)
      BF_01 <- c(BF_01, bf)
      
      BF_post <- c(BF_post, bf/(bf +1)) #posterior probabilities 
      
    }
    
    BIC_averages0 <- c(BIC_averages0, mean(BIC_H0))
    BIC_averages1 <- c(BIC_averages1, mean(BIC_H1))
    BF_01_averages <- c(BF_01_averages, mean(BF_01))
    BF_post_averages <- c(BF_post_averages, mean(BF_post))
    log_averages <- c(log_averages, mean(log(BF_01)))
    
  }
  results <- cbind(BIC_averages0, BIC_averages1, BF_01_averages, BF_post_averages, log_averages)
  return(results)
}

Discussion

If we look at the posterior probabilities, In both approaches, as n increases precision level increases such that standard error decreases however, for BIC approach, BF values for higher n are lower when H0 is true.

If we compare the posterior probabilities plots as follow:

With higher n we would expect both more precise (lower standard error) and higher evidence. In both approaches, as n increases precision level also increases such that standard error decreases and amount of evidence increases such that the peak of the graph is going up. However, in BIC, both precision level and the amount of evidence increases less. If we compare both graph, in the second graph, the difference between standard errors of the lines is higher compared to BIC (the first graph). Also, in the second graph,as n increases the peak of the graph is going up higher.

From the plots, we can also observe that BIC approach is overall more precise with lower standard error whereas normal approach has more evidence especially for higher sample sizes.

Bayes Factor for Multiple Testing

bf_multiple_testing generates network autocorrelation model data using the specified parameters as input variables. Then it tests the following hypotheses for the simulated data and calculates \(B_{01}\) using the Savage-dickey ratio method. The function uses a multivariate normal prior with a mean of zero and variance equal to the expected information matrix for one information, that is \({\sf N}(0, \hat{\sigma^2_{\beta}}/\sqrt{g})\).

  • \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} = 0\)
  • \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} < 0\)
  • \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} > 0\)
  • \(H_{u}: \beta_{1} \in \mathbb{R}\)
    and
    returns 20X6 matrix:
  • In the columns respectively: Average \(B_{01}\), \(B_{02}\), \(B_{12}\) and average of \(log(B_{01})\), \(log(B_{02})\), \(log(B_{12})\).
  • In the rows: Beta sequence of 20 between -2 and 2.

where,

  • \(\beta_{01}\) = \(\frac{\beta_{u0}}{\beta_{u1}}\)
  • \(\beta_{02}\) = \(\frac{\beta_{u0}} {\beta_{u2}}\)
  • \(\beta_{12}\) = \(\frac{\beta_{u1}} {\beta_{u2}}\)


Input variables:

  • sigma2 : \(\sigma^{2}\)
  • n : \(g\), network size
  • rho : \(\rho\), network effect
  • d : \(d\), network density


bf_multiple_testing <- function(sigma2 = 1, n = 50, rho = 0.2, d = 0.2){
  #Beta Sequence 
  beta_seq <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = 20)
  
  BF01_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  BF02_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  BF12_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  BF01_log_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  BF02_log_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  BF12_log_averages <- rep(NA, 20)
  for (i in 1: 20){
    #Beta Array
    beta <- cbind(rep(1, 1000),rep(beta_seq[i], 1000))
    #Bayes Factor Arrays for for Beta Estimators
    B01 <- rep(NA, 1000)
    B02 <- rep(NA, 1000)
    B12 <- rep(NA, 1000)
    #Network Autocorrelation Data Generation 
    
    for (j in 1:1000){
      set.seed(123)
      Wadj <- sna::rgraph(n, tprob = d, mode = "graph")
      W <- sna::make.stochastic(Wadj, mode = "row") 
      X <- matrix(c(rep(1, n), rnorm(n*1)), nrow=n, ncol=2)
      
      y <- c((solve(diag(n) - rho*W))%*%(X%*%beta[j,] + rnorm(n, sd = sqrt(sigma2))))
      y <- y - mean(y)
      
      
      #H0: Beta = 0 
      #H1: Beta < 0 
      #H2: Beta > 0 
      #Hu: Beta  R
      
      #network autocorrelation model fit
      model1 <- sna::lnam(y, X, W)
      
      #Bu0 
      post0 <- dnorm(0, mean = model1$beta[2,1], model1$beta.se[2]) #posterior distribution
      prior0 <- dnorm(0, mean = 0, model1$beta.se[2]*sqrt(n)) #unit information prior distribution 
      fact0 <- post0/prior0
      
      #Bu1
      post1 <- pnorm(0, mean = model1$beta[2,1], model1$beta.se[2], lower.tail = TRUE) #posterior distribution
      prior1 <- pnorm(0, mean = 0, model1$beta.se[2]*sqrt(n), lower.tail = TRUE) #unit information prior distribution 
      fact1 <- post1/prior1
      
      #Bu2
      post2 <- pnorm(0, mean = model1$beta[2,1], model1$beta.se[2], lower.tail = FALSE) #posterior distribution
      prior2 <- pnorm(0, mean = 0, model1$beta.se[2]*sqrt(n), lower.tail = FALSE) #unit information prior distribution 
      fact2 <- post2/prior2
      
      #BAYES FACTOR CALCULATION
      
      B01[j] <- fact0/fact1
      B02[j] <- fact0/fact2
      B12[j] <- fact1/fact2
      
    }
    
    BF01_averages[i] <- mean(B01)
    BF02_averages[i] <- mean(B02)
    BF12_averages[i] <- mean(B12)
    BF01_log_averages[i] <- mean(log(B01))
    BF02_log_averages[i] <- mean(log(B02))
    BF12_log_averages[i] <- mean(log(B12))
  }
  results <- cbind(BF01_averages, BF02_averages, BF12_averages, BF01_log_averages, BF02_log_averages, BF12_log_averages)
  return(results)
}

Real Data Examples

In the following, we applied the two-sided and multiple Bayes factor hypothesis testing to two data sets from the literature to analyze the performance of Bayes factor test for \(\beta\) coefficients. First, we tested the hypotheses \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) versus \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\) for each variable with Savage-Dickey ratio method and BIC approximation. Second, we conducted multiple hypothesis testing for the same variables and test the hypotheses \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} = 0\) versus \(H_{1}: \beta_{1} < 0\) versus \(H_{2}: \beta_{1} > 0\).


Boston Housing Data 

#install.packages("spdep")
library(spdep)
data(boston)

Data Preparation 

#Adjacency Matrix 
W_boston <- nb2mat(boston.soi, glist=NULL, style="W", zero.policy=NULL)
W <- sna::make.stochastic(W_boston, mode = "row")

#X Matrix
X_boston <- cbind("Intercept" = 1,
                  "CRIM" = boston.c$CRIM,
                  "ZN" = boston.c$ZN,
                  "INDUS" = boston.c$INDUS,
                  "CHAS" = boston.c$CHAS,
                  "I(NOX2)" = I(boston.c$NOX^2),
                  "I(RM2)" = I(boston.c$RM^2),
                  "AGE" = boston.c$AGE,
                  "log(DIS)" = log(boston.c$DIS),
                  "log(RAD)" = log(boston.c$RAD),
                  "TAX" = boston.c$TAX,
                  "PTRATIO" = boston.c$PTRATIO,
                  "B" = boston.c$B,
                  "log(LSTAT)" = log(boston.c$LSTAT)
)


#Vector of responses 
y_boston <- log(boston.c$CMEDV)

NAM Model Fit using lnam 

model_boston <- sna::lnam(y_boston, X_boston, W)
summary(model_boston)

Savage Dickey Ratio Function for Two-Sided and Multiple Hypothesis Testing


The following function savage_testing fits the specified network data and tests its \(\beta\) coefficients using the Savage-Dickey ratio with uniform prior for both two-sided and multiple hypothesis testing. In two-sided test,it tests hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) and \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\); In multiple hypothesis test, it tests the hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} = 0\) versus \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} < 0\) versus \(H_{0}: \beta_{1} > 0\) versus \(H_{u}: \beta_{1} \in \mathbb{R}\).


The function returns n X 4 matrix, where n refers to the number of \(\beta\) coefficients to be tested:

  • In the columns respectively: \(B_{01}\) for the two-sided test, and \(B_{01}\) \(B_{02}\), \(B_{12}\) for the multiple test.
  • In the rows: The exogenous variables of interest


Input variables:

  • y : a vector of responses
  • X : a vector or matrix of covariates; if the latter, each column should contain a single covariate
  • W : Adjacency Matrix
  • n : Number of \(\beta\) coefficients to be tested
  • g : \(g\), network size


savage_testing <- function(y = "responses", X = "covariates", W = "Adjacency Matrix", 
                           n = "number of beta to be tested", g = "network size"){
 
   model <- sna::lnam(y, X, W) #model fit
   
   #TWO-SIDED HYPOTHESIS TEST 

   B01 <-c() #Bayes Factor array for B01 in two-sided test
  
  for (i in 2:(n+1)){
    post<- dnorm(0, mean = model$beta[i,1], model$beta.se[i]) #posterior distribution
    prior <- dnorm(0, mean = model$beta[i,1], model$beta.se[i]*sqrt(g)) #unit information prior distribution
    B01 <- c(B01, post/prior)
  }
  
  #MULTIPLE HYPOTHESIS TESTING

  B01_m <- c() #Bayes Factor array for B01
  B02_m <- c() #Bayes Factor array for B02
  B12_m <- c() #Bayes Factor array for B12
  
  for (j in 2:(n+1)){
    
    #B0u 
    post0 <- dnorm(0, mean = model$beta[j,1], model$beta.se[j]) #posterior distribution
    prior0 <- dnorm(0, mean = 0, model$beta.se[j]*sqrt(g)) #unit information prior distribution 
    fact0 <- post0/prior0
    
    #B1u
    post1 <- pnorm(0, mean = model$beta[j,1], model$beta.se[j], lower.tail = TRUE) #posterior distribution
    prior1 <- pnorm(0, mean = 0, model$beta.se[j]*sqrt(g), lower.tail = TRUE) #unit information prior distribution 
    fact1 <- post1/prior1
    
    #B2u
    post2 <- pnorm(0, mean = model$beta[j,1], model$beta.se[j], lower.tail = FALSE) #posterior distribution
    prior2 <- pnorm(0, mean = 0, model$beta.se[j]*sqrt(g), lower.tail = FALSE) #unit information prior distribution 
    fact2 <- post2/prior2
    
    B01_m <- c(B01_m, fact0/fact1)
    B02_m <- c(B02_m, fact0/fact2)
    B12_m <- c(B12_m, fact1/fact2)
  }
  
  results <- cbind(B01, B01_m, B02_m, B12_m)
  rownames(results) <- names(model$beta)[-1] # assigning the names of the covariates to row names
  return(results)
}


Testing the Example Data Sets 

savage_dickey_test_boston <- round(savage_testing(model = model_boston, n = 13, g = 506), digits = 5) #BOSTON HOUSING PRICES DATA
savage_dickey_test_crime <- savage_testing(y_crime, X_crime, W_crime, n = 2, g = 49) #CRIME DATA


BIC Approximation for Two-Sided Hypothesis Testing


The following function bic_function fits the specified network data and tests its \(\beta\) coefficients using the BIC approximation for two-sided hypothesis testing. In particular, it tests hypotheses against each other: \(H_{0}: \beta = 0\) and \(H_{1}: \beta \neq 0\).


The function returns n X 1 matrix, where n refers to the number of \(\beta\) coefficients to be tested:

  • In the column respectively: \(B_{01}\) for the two-sided test
  • In the rows: The exogenous variables of interest


Input variables:

  • y : a vector of responses
  • X : a vector or matrix of covariates; if the latter, each column should contain a single covariate
  • W : Adjacency Matrix
  • g : \(g\), network size
  • n1 : Number of \(\beta\) coefficients to be tested
  • n2 : Total number of parameters in the full model


bic_function <- function(y = "responses", X = "covariates", W = "Adjacency Matrix", g = "network size",
                         n1 = "number of beta to be tested", 
                         n2 = "total number of parameters in the full model"){
  
  model <- sna::lnam(y, X, W) #full model fit
  full_model_bic <- -2*(model$lnlik.model) + n2*log(g) #BIC of the full model 
    
  BayesFactor <- matrix(NA, nrow = n1) #Bayes factor matrix for B01

  for (i in 2:(n1+1)){
    covariate_model <- sna::lnam(y, X[,c(-i)], W)
    covariate_model_bic <- -2*(covariate_model$lnlik.model) + (n2-1)*log(g)
    B01 <- exp(-(covariate_model_bic - full_model_bic)/2)
    BayesFactor[(i-1), ] <- B01
  }
  
  rownames(BayesFactor) <- names(model$beta)[-1] # assigning the names of the covariates to row names
  return(BayesFactor)
}


Testing the Example Data Sets 

bic_test_boston <- bic_function( y = y_boston, X = X_boston, W = W, g = 506, n1 = 13, n2 = 16) #BOSTON HOUSING PRICES DATA
bic_test_crime <- bic_function(y = y_crime, X = X_crime, W = W_crime, g = 49, n1 = 2, n2 = 5) #CRIME DATA
